      <h2>Which Box for Which Trade?</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Electricians:</strong> UWS EC10322 (4.4★) or EC10473 (4.5★). Crossover format, waist-height access, enough depth for meters and hand tools.</li>
        <li><strong>Framers / Carpenters:</strong> Weather Guard 127-0-03 saddle box (5.0★). Deep side compartments for levels and saws, center bed open for lumber.</li>
        <li><strong>Landscapers:</strong> Garvee Steel Underbody (4.5★). Keeps the bed completely clear for mulch, mowers, and stone.</li>
        <li><strong>HVAC / Plumbing:</strong> UWS EC10473 (4.5★). Room for copper, fittings, meters, and power tools. Low profile preserves rear visibility for city driving.</li>
        <li><strong>Fleet managers:</strong> Weather Guard (5.0★) for durability. Fleet feedback consistently highlights Weather Guard's build consistency across multiple vehicles.</li>
        <li><strong>Fifth-wheel / gooseneck users:</strong> Northern Tool Slim Low Profile (3.6★) or Garvee Underbody (4.5★) — both leave the center bed clear for trailer hitches.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
      <p>If you can only buy one box for a primary work truck, the <strong>UWS EC10473</strong> (4.5 stars) is the strongest all-around value in the crossover category — heavy-wall aluminum, low profile, RigidCore lid, and ample 69-inch capacity at a price point below Weather Guard. If budget is secondary to maximum commercial-grade build quality, the <strong>Weather Guard 127-0-03</strong> (5.0 stars) is the undisputed top of the line. For trades that need the bed clear, the <strong>Garvee Steel Underbody Box</strong> (4.5 stars) delivers solid steel security in a space-saving format.</p>
      <p>No matter which you choose, pair it with a quality mounting kit — your $500+ toolbox deserves better than thin J-hooks.</p>

